<pagesize pagetype="Letter" orientation="portrait" width="8.500000" height="11.000000" units="in" page-scale="1.000000"/>
<section xid="52" props="column-line:off; columns:3; dom-dir:ltr; section-space-after:0.2500in; page-margin-footer:0.5in; page-margin-header:0.5in; text-align:left; section-max-column-height:0.0000in">
<p style="Normal" xid="53"><c props="font-weight:bold; font-family:Piboto; font-size:10pt">NOCTIVAGOUS</c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="51"><c props="font-weight:bold; font-size:12pt"></c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="50"><c props="font-weight:bold; font-size:24pt"></c><c props="font-weight:bold; font-family:URW Bookman; font-size:18pt">An Overview of AI Technology Today</c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="54"><c props="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt; color:000000; text-decoration:none; text-position:normal; font-weight:bold; font-style:normal; lang:en-US"></c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="55"><c props="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt; color:000000; text-decoration:none; text-position:normal; font-weight:bold; font-style:normal; lang:en-US"></c><c props="font-family:Quicksand Medium; font-size:10pt; color:000000; text-decoration:none; text-position:normal; font-weight:bold; font-style:normal; lang:en-US">John Pratt</c></p>
<p style="Heading 2" xid="1"><c>The Smoke And Mirrors </c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="3"><c></c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="21"><c></c><c props="font-size:20pt">T</c><c>he AI technology that sits behind ChatGPT cannot, in fact, remember anything said to it. It is re-sent the entire conversation every time you add a question. It has to be told that there is a conversation taking place, too, so that it knows how to process the text. It is called a Large Language Model (LLM). When used by itself, an LLM just answers a prompt, stops, and retains nothing. The only way it can chat is through various non-AI software add-ons. To produce a chat, OpenAI positions the LLM in a programmatic flow to line up its responses in a conversational format, and they add a memory for it through traditional software techniques. But it cannot manage any of the chat by itself. Also, when it says, "Thank you for correcting me," that is just a by-product of its training. It cannot update its own information in response right then because its contents are fixed. It is a static, artificial neural network that cannot be changed without the external effort of either "fine-tuning" or complete retraining (which means starting over with training). The latest Grok is said to learn every week but that is because it undergoes weekly fine-tuning. So, ChatGPT, Grok, Claude, etc. are definitely contrived with respect to the AI being able to chat with the user. The LLM is very powerful when given all of the scaffolding, the chats are very useful, but essentially this is a makeshift situation when it comes to the AI's interactive capabilities. All related technologies, like "agents," are similar adaptations connected to the LLM.</c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="63"><c></c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="4"><c></c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="6"><c props="font-weight:bold">During Training, The LLM Has to Be Provided Q and A Text</c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="49"><c props="font-weight:bold"></c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="7"><c>After training, taking months on thousands of high-end machines, the LLM exists only as a next word predictor, though one that is immensely complex in its association. At this stage it is called the base model. If the base model is going to respond to questions with answers-- and not just try to complete the text provided to it-- it has to be trained on thousands of manually crafted Q and As. If the AI companies don't train it with these, it will just continue any provided text, e.g. "What is the capital of France?" </c><c props="font-family:D050000L">Þ</c><c props="font-family:Times New Roman"></c><c> "Paris, located on the Seine River, is known for…" So, after training the LLM, they feed it their database of Q and As to shape its responses for chats. Then it follows this Q and A pattern and will answer questions, e.g. "What is the capital of France? </c><c props="font-family:D050000L">Þ</c><c props="font-family:Times New Roman"></c><c> "Paris.", meaning that it will follow this for its word predictions. The LLM is a complicated pattern matching AI that is deeply trained with high compute resources over a long period of time. The value comes from the emergent capabilities that form during the training that go beyond mere statistical associations. Without the AI companies ever having programmed such features, the model can translate, do math, perform work on text, check spelling, and a lot more. So, it is not something to take lightly as a technology of course, but at its current stage of development it relies on manual processes to produce correctly formed answers in response to instructions. </c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="48"><c></c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="8"><c>When there is a new version of ChatGPT, Grok, etc., it is because they trained a completely new LLM with the latest techniques and greater compute resources, but unless these fundamental aspects are upgraded by researchers, it will always require scaffolding and extra processes for conversations. The investments made in the latest high-end LLMs are huge: over $100 million for each major version number, with some estimates reaching $500 million and above for the latest OpenAI model, GPT 5. Version 5 will be very expensive like this and then point updates cost less (5.1, 5.2, 5.3, etc.) because they make changes from the foundation. </c></p>
<p style="Heading 2" xid="9"><c></c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="10"><c props="font-weight:bold">How Generative AI Works: Probability, Training </c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="42"><c props="font-weight:bold"></c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="11"><c>All generative AIs—for chat, images, and video— are founded on the same approach: they're probability machines built from enormous artificial neural networks that predict what data should look like, and they then produce output for whichever format they were designed. They carry patterns they've learned from being trained on vast databases of real examples. </c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="43"><c></c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="12"><c>• </c><c props="font-weight:bold">For chat/text:</c><c> the AI model predicts the next word (actually a piece of the word) that's most likely to come after what it's already written, then the next one, and so on—like a gigantic autocomplete that keeps going. The technology begins as autocomplete. (The words are constructed out of "tokens," which are pieces of words that range from a single character (e.g. “h”) to several (e.g. “hello”) for the most common cases. It is actually predicting tokens, not words.) </c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="44"><c></c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="13"><c>• </c><c props="font-weight:bold">For images:</c><c> the AI model starts with random noise, places it on the image file, and then repeatedly predicts "what pixels would make this less noisy and match the prompt?" It cleans up the noise bit by bit until a clear picture appears. (It received training that linked descriptive text to images so that a text prompt can produce image data.)</c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="45"><c></c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="14"><c>• </c><c props="font-weight:bold">For video:</c><c> the AI model does something very similar to images, but across time—it predicts what the pixels should be in a whole sequence of frames, cleaning noise or predicting the next moments so the video moves naturally. (Video training data includes not only the moving images but also the descriptive text that goes with them, and thus after being trained the neural network can construct frames in sequence in response to a text prompt.) </c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="46"><c></c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="15"><c>In each case, the AI is asking: "Given what I've got so far and the prompt, what's the most probable way the data (words, pixels, or moving pixels) should continue or look?" Then it picks the best guesses and builds the output. For chat, how much text of a certain opinion or viewpoint the model was given during training will weight its responses in that direction. It is predicting the next word or portion of a word based on what it was trained on. That single core idea—trained probability prediction over data—powers chatbots, image generators, and video generators today. The differences are mostly in what kind of data they're predicting (words vs. pixels vs. pixels over time) and how they step through the predictions. As stated, all of this is implemented through enormous neural networks—vast systems of interconnected nodes inspired in a most reduced and simple way by the human brain—that require immense computing power and months of mathematical training on billions of examples. These artificial neural networks operate in extremely high-dimensional spaces (far beyond our everyday three dimensions), allowing them to detect and combine subtle, complex patterns that produce such strikingly realistic results.  </c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="57"><c></c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="59"><c>In an artificial neural network, the interconnected circles in typical diagrams represent artificial neurons (also called nodes), each of which acts as a simple computational unit. There are numerical values, called weights, that are not assigned directly to these nodes but rather to the connections (the lines or arrows) linking one neuron to another. Training begins with these connection weights initialized to small random values, providing the network with an unbiased starting point. As training data flows through the network, the learning algorithm compares the model's predictions to the actual targets, calculates the resulting error, and iteratively adjusts the weights (and biases) to minimize that error. “The capital of France is " will be compared with the target “Paris.” Over many iterations, this process gradually refines the strength of each connection, enabling the network to capture increasingly complex patterns and make more accurate predictions.</c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="60"><c></c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="62"><c></c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="17"><c props="font-weight:bold">Extra: Self-Driving</c><c> </c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="47"><c></c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="18"><c>Self-driving AI continues the AI technology approach just mentioned: it's built on large neural networks trained to predict the most probable next action or state based on vast amounts of real-world data. The core idea remains probabilistic prediction, but instead of predicting the next token (text), pixel (image), or frame sequence (video), self-driving systems predict the next vehicle control signals—like steering angle, acceleration, braking force, or trajectory adjustments—given the current sensory input and context. It is trained on billions of miles of real driving data from the fleet—video clips labeled or selected for safe human driving behavior. The model predicts the most likely next control actions that a skilled human driver would take in similar situations. So, it is generally not reasoning from programmed principles in real-time in response to the environment like a person might expect. </c><c props="font-family:D050000L">o</c><c props="font-family:Times New Roman"></c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="19"><c></c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="20"><c></c></p>
</section>
